SIMPLE: respiration
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Respiration
<hw>Res`pi*ra"tion</hw> <pr>(r?s`p?*r?"sh?n)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[L. <ets>respiratio</ets>: cf. F. <ets>respiration</ets>. See
<er>Respire</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>The act of respiring or
breathing again, or catching one's breath.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Relief from toil or suffering: rest.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Till the day⟦br⟧
Appear of <qex>respiration</qex> to the just⟦br⟧
And vengeance to the wicked.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Interval; intermission.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Bp. Hall.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>The act of resping or
breathing; the act of taking in and giving out air; the aggregate of
those processes bu which oxygen is introduced into the system, and
carbon dioxide, or carbonic acid, removed.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<note><p>⟦hand⟧ Respiration in the higher animals is divided into:
(<stype>a</stype>) <xex>Internal respiration</xex>, or the interchange
of oxygen and carbonic acid between the cells of the body and the
bathing them, which in one sense is a process of nutrition.
(<stype>b</stype>) <xex>External respiration</xex>, or the gaseous
interchange taking place in the special respiratory organs, the lungs.
This constitutes respiration proper. <rj><au>Gamgee.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p> In the respiration of plants oxygen is likewise absorbed and
carbonic acid exhaled, but in the light this process is obscured by
another process which goes on with more vigor, in which the plant
inhales and absorbs carbonic acid and exhales free oxygen.⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></note>

<p><ent>Respirational</ent>⟦br⟧
